{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506895"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2591"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2591"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.07,0.05,0.39,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79074"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2591"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64426"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"2917"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27074"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79074"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old male presents to his nephrologist. He was referred due to ankle swelling and deranged biochemistry. After initial evaluation and further investigations he underwent a renal biopsy, which was normal under light microscopy but there was effacement of the foot processes on electron microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EToday, his blood results are significant for low albumin (20g/L) and high total cholesterol (9mmol/L). His urine dipstick is positive 4+ for protein.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate way to manage his high cholesterol initially?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start him on atorvastatin","Encourage regular exercise","Trial a fibrate","Trial a course of steroids","Advise him to follow a low unsaturated fat diet"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stem and blood results suggest a diagnosis of nephrotic syndrome, as demonstrated by heavy proteinuria, hypoalbuminaemia, clinical oedema and hyperlipidaemia. In this case the cause of the nephrotic syndrome, as suggested by the biopsy results is minimal change disease. Suggested by the name, the pathological hallmark for this condition is the absence of changes under light microscope, but effacement of the foot processes under electron microscope.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to recognise that the hyperlipidaemia in the context of nephrotic syndrome does not require lipid lowering medications and will not respond effectively to lifestyle changes. The treatment requires treating the underlying nephrotic syndrome and heavy proteinuria, which is driving the hyperlipidaemia. There may be some role for these medications and lifestyle changes in chronic unremitting nephrotic syndrome, but in the acute phase of nephrotic syndrome the management of hyperlipidaemia centres around managing the cause of the nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore\u003Cstrong\u003E, starting him on atorvastatin or starting a fibrate\u003C/strong\u003E would not be effective and are not recommended in this case. \u003Cstrong\u003EExercise\u003C/strong\u003E has been shown to increase HDL levels, and likely have a positive effect on cholesterol levels in the general population. But the underlying pathophysiology of the hyperlipidaemia is not driven by lifestyle factors in nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiet\u003C/strong\u003E plays an important role in hyperlipidaemia, but the advice should be for patients to avoid saturated fats rather than unsaturated fats, which actually have positive impacts on health and lipids. Similarly, diet would be unlikely to influence hyperlipidaemia in nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the most appropriate management of his high cholesterol is to treat the underlying condition. General approaches would be through fluid and salt restriction, the use of an ACE-I and in some cases steroids. Hence a \u003Cstrong\u003Etrial of steroids\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to treat his minimal change disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperlipidaemia in nephrotic syndrome does not warrant lipid lowering therapy","Steroids are often trialled in the management of primary nephrotic syndrome, such as in minimal change disease"],"references":["Kodner C. Diagnosis and Management of Nephrotic Syndrome in Adults. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Mar 15;93(6):479-85. PMID: 26977832 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26977832/","Valeri A, Gelfand J, Blum C, Appel GB. Treatment of the hyperlipidemia of the nephrotic syndrome: a controlled trial. Am J Kidney Dis. 1986 Dec;8(6):388-96. doi: 10.1016/s0272-6386(86)80164-0. PMID: 3544820. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3544820/","Agrawal S, Zaritsky JJ, Fornoni A, Smoyer WE. Dyslipidaemia in nephrotic syndrome: mechanisms and treatment [published correction appears in Nat Rev Nephrol. 2017 Dec 13;14 (1):70]. Nat Rev Nephrol. 2018;14(1):57-70. doi:10.1038/nrneph.2017.155 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29176657/","Vivarelli M, Massella L, Ruggiero B, Emma F. Minimal Change Disease. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2017 Feb 7;12(2):332-345. doi: 10.2215/CJN.05000516. Epub 2016 Dec 9. PMID: 27940460; PMCID: PMC5293332. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27940460/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64426"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2591"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64426"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T14:33:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T14:34:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2591"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79074"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":